##"closing the city" in January: an illustration of life in Wuhan

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. Linkage of three medical, bridge capital, direct health

After a 31-day ordeal, the prevention and control of the Wuhan epidemic has moved from disorder to order, but the life of tens of millions of residents has only just begun from disorder to order, and the social and economic life in this core area of the epidemic has fully recovered, and a lot of challenges

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On February 11,2020, community workers at Wuchang Shelter Hospital, Hongshan Stadium, Wuhan, welcomed the first 28 patients to leave the hospital. Photo / China News

Wen | CAIJING special correspondent Wuhan Xinna, Liu Yiqin, Wang Xiao Caijing correspondent, Xin Ying

Editor | Wang Xiao

On the morning of February 23,2020, Liu Jing went to a doctor at a shelter hospital in Wuhan to ask about a waiting list for nucleic acid tests, "Each ward has an average of seven test quotas per day, and the patients can queue up before meeting the requirements. After two days, they can be tested, and they can be discharged if they meet the standards, " Liu told Caijing.

A month has passed since the city was shut down. Public Transport in Wuhan will be suspended from 10:00 on January 23. Airport and railway stations will be closed until further notice.

Liu Jing did not see her name, but she was not anxious, relieved to wait in line, waiting to be released from the hospital, waiting to see the two children who had been separated for a month, waiting for everything to return to normal.

Since February, the streets of Wuhan have been almost deserted, with police officers visible every two or three corners. On both sides of the street, supermarkets, convenience stores and fruit shops were mostly closed. The only way to feel alive is to walk past the delivery man.

People living in high-rise residential areas want to see the city, only through the windows, "everyone is bored to see every day on the glass, people walking their dogs will be taken photos in the hair group. ". A local resident told CAIJING.

In the face of super-strong transmission capacity of new coronavirus, Wuhan is fighting a "quarantine" war, only cut off the spread of disease sources, in order to stop the spread of the epidemic.

Over the course of a month, the battlefield has expanded from the isolation of the hospital to the entire city, and every community has been isolated as an island.

The past week has been the most intense period of segregation in Wuhan since the city was sealed off. Although Wuhan has been closed to the public since Feb. 11, the few supermarkets that were open on Feb. 16 were packed in the morning, with people wearing masks allowed to enter through semi-closed passageways after body temperature checks. However, after 6 days, supermarkets have not allowed individuals into the purchase, only group purchase.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Walmart's supermarket in Wuhan. Photograph by Liu Yiqin, Caijing reporter

On February 17th, 19th, Wuhan launched a three-day centralized net-cleaning, community-based, aimed at thoroughly screening all kinds of patients and close contacts. Epidemic Prevention and control into a critical moment, in order to hold the city of Wuhan, all Wuhan people have made sacrifices.

After a 31-day ordeal, the prevention and control of the epidemic in Wuhan has moved from disorder to order, but the life of tens of millions of residents has only just begun from disorder to order, and the socio-economic life in this core area of the epidemic has fully recovered, and a lot of challenges.

"Now there's an endless line. "

Around January 21, when the Wuhan epidemic alert sounded, most people were still immersed in the happy atmosphere of family reunion during the Spring Festival holiday.

Two days before the "closure, " Wang Chen, a native of Wuhan, was planning a road trip for the Spring Festival. Friends around him were also discussing how to play the New Year. Recalling those days, he felt as if everyone was worried about Wuhan, only the Wuhan people themselves did not feel it.

"before the city was shut down, the Wuhan government behaved too normally and even planned to give away free tickets to the scenic spots, " Wang told Caijing.

A professor at the Wuhan University led a team of more than a dozen students to a community health center on Jan. 20 for routine research. "I was a public health researcher, but nobody knew the extent of the epidemic at the time, " he said

Although Liu Jing has been aware of the risks, but this day is the first seven father-in-law, although the phone refused all relatives and friends to come to the home worship, but the same community brother and sister-in-law always have to sit together. "Why don't you stay for dinner? " Liu Jing was impressed with her words. She said later that she would not eat, then some slight cough sister-in-law, also became her only contact with the source of the disease.

On January 22, Hubei started the second-level Emergency Response Mechanism for public health emergencies. That night, Wuhan will be "closed" news out. A local policeman was also the first to see the news on the Internet, and soon received an order, "not to leave Wuhan. Stand by. "

At this time, in addition to the 61 local hospitals in Wuhan that have opened fever clinics, the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission announced on January 22 the second batch of seven designated hospitals for treating new cases of coronary pneumonia, with the help of seven general hospitals, more than 3000 beds have been allocated for the treatment of suspected and confirmed cases of new coronary pneumonia.

While most people still talk about the "city closure" information is difficult to distinguish true and false, the symptoms of the crowd has been overloaded to Wuhan hospitals. Outside the hospital was a line of registered patients, registered people began to run in various hospitals.

Just after midnight on January 23, a doctor at a designated hospital in Wuhan was on pins and needles, "Several designated hospitals are in the Central Wuhan area, " he told Caijing by telephone. "patients who can not be admitted to the hospitals are moving from hospital to hospital. They have become a mobile source of infection and must be controlled as soon as possible. "

The number of fever clinics in Wuhan surged to about 13,000 the day before the city was closed, and has remained above 10,000 a day since then until January 28.

At 2:00 am on January 23, the news of the city's closure was officially announced. This was also the most stressful day for hospitals in Wuhan in January, with fever outpatient visits reaching a peak of 14,486.

"closed city" on the same day, Liu Yang was sent to the designated hospital in Wuhan Seven Hospital support. By then the line for the fever clinic at seven hospitals had snaked into the street outside. After more than 20 hours of waiting in line, on January 23 at 2:00 am, Li Fan's father finally received infusion treatment in the outpatient observation room of the seven hospitals. Inside and outside the observation room, crowds of people wearing masks.

In the previous 24 hours, Li and his family had visited four hospitals in Wuhan.

On January 24th, the eve of the year of the boxer rat, Liu Yang remembers nothing but a dark mass of people. He was surrounded by people, surrounded by noise, coughing and complaining.

Outside the crowded hospitals, there are still countless patients. On January 24th Jiang Chaoliang, then Hubei's party chief, demanded that Wuhan treat all suspected patients unconditionally and effectively isolate them. Subsequently, Wuhan decided to implement the central city area motor vehicle ban management, Fire Mountain, Raytheon Mountain Hospital project has started.

On January 30 and February 1, the government of the Kong Hon District of Wuhan, where the South China Seafood Market is located, twice asked for instructions from the medical treatment team of the new Wuhan Pneumonia Prevention and Control Headquarters and Vice Mayor Chen Xiangxin, please coordinate the admission of patients.

"there are still 142 confirmed patients who can not be admitted to hospitals, including 65 at the Red Cross Hospital and 77 at other hospitals. Their condition is extremely critical. ". This is the "Caijing" reporter learned at that time, the Kong Hon district four designated hospitals, in poor medical conditions, lack of medical staff, medical resources are limited circumstances, the admission of a large number of patients.

On January 28, Liu Jing's sister-in-law called her to tell her that during a CT scan at the hospital, "the lung infection was ground-glass-like, " but there was no way to do a nucleic acid test and she had to be isolated at home for 10 days.

"I feel sorry for Wuhan. "

It was the first time that Wang Chen had spent the new year alone. He planned to go to the supermarket to buy some delicious food. He went to several supermarkets, the shelves were empty, so he had to buy some boxes of instant noodles. When he got home, the water was cut off and he could only eat dried instant noodles. "I've come back to help you, but you're going to starve me to death, " he wrote in his circle of friends

January 25, the first day of the Lunar New Year. In the morning, Wang Chen opened the curtains and looked out at the foggy sky and empty streets. "there was no atmosphere at all for the New Year. "

"It was like a giant collapsed, " Wang said. "I didn't feel sorry for myself. I felt bad for Wuhan. "

Since then, the number of outbreaks has risen day by day, with people in Wuhan and the outside world worried every day. In mid February, when the outbreak data seemed to be improving, Wuhan announced on February 11th that it was adopting a closed community management system in which one person per household could go out shopping every three days.

"Our community in the group every day shouting do not go out, said is a pass to the street, otherwise someone will check out to see if you have proof of the unit. My friend works in a hospital, and she can only go to work if she has a hospital certificate,"said Li Xiaoyi, she did not go out in the past week, only on February 22 to go out, "I went to pick up the express, he asked to pick up. ".

Li Xiaoyi also wanted to go out and buy some things back, but the shops are closed, convenience stores are not personal, can only be ordered online shopping platform, and then delivery workers into the community.

Since February 16, community management more strict, block all the community, some old-style community even with wooden boards to block the intersection. Some large supermarkets no longer accept any personal consumption, must be community-based, after the issuance of a certificate to buy goods. Supermarkets and vegetable markets are no longer accessible to individuals.

Li Xiaoyi has joined more than 10 wechat shopping groups, including vegetable groups, rice and flour groups, which are even subdivided into group purchases of cat food. "It's a big deal to eat now, " she said. "wechat groups go from chatting with eyes open to eating with lights out. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Above, a supermarket in Wuchang District, Wuhan, on February 16 and below, in the fruit and vegetables section on February 22. Photo by Wang Xiao, CAIJING reporter

As a volunteer, Wang continued to campaign for help messages that mostly came from ordinary residents, unable to buy food, medicine, milk powder or dog food or cat litter.

How to ensure the daily life of these residents is a new task. To solve the problem of buying vegetables, Wuhan has organised nine e-commerce companies to launch "community group purchase of vegetables" . But online shopping platforms can not cover all corners, volunteer Chen Xingxu told Caijing. The variety of dishes that can be purchased in community groups is limited, the prices are higher, and some times are not fresh, and many elderly people living alone will not use e-commerce group buying.

An owner said in the owner wechat group, afternoon to help her buy fish, she has been thinking that her mother-in-law to her son's home. Old People do not have wechat, the source of external information is limited.

For a hospital bed

Supplies were procured and distributed by the community, and the screening of fever patients by community staff continued in a medium-sized community with close to 10,000 inhabitants.

On Feb. 3, the top five people did not return overnight outside the nucleic acid testing room of Wuhan No. 7 Hospital. The middle-aged man at the front tightened his coat. "I've been sitting at the front since 8 o'clock last night. ".

But the rules of the day have changed. At 8:00 a.m. , a tall doctor in a Hazmat suit carries pages of A4 printed paper listing serial numbers, names and other information. Liu Yang used a megaphone to shout out to the anxiously waiting crowd outside the door that the person who had called the previous day could not have his nucleic acid tested until today, which meant he had to be on the list.

The quota for the day is 190. The line loosened, and, with loud grumbling, people flocked to the door. After nearly 20 minutes, the crowd gradually calmed down and everyone had to accept the new rules.

During that time, Liu Yang recalls, he repeated the same answers over and over again -- when to start testing, where to line up, how to get the results -- and his tape got hoarse from the intense exercise.

This outstanding change, from Wuhan "should receive receive receive, should inspect thoroughly inspect" the war.

On the evening of February 2, the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters held a video dispatch meeting, requiring "four focus" : confirmed, suspected, fever and close contacts are all centralized treatment and isolation.

All the so-called admission, mainly seriously ill patients, received critical hospitals and designated hospitals; mild patients, are arranged to enter the various shelter hospitals and isolation points.

CAIJING reporter learned that on the morning of February 5, the Wuhan New Crown Pneumonia Epidemic Prevention and control headquarters held a meeting, requiring all districts in the next two days, that is, until February 7 at the latest, Wuhan all suspected cases of nucleic acid testing. In addition to the detection of suspected cases, the meeting also proposed to seek admission of all confirmed patients at 2400 hours on the evening of February 5.

On February 8, Liu Jing had an attack and went to the hospital for tests. She was diagnosed with new crown pneumonia on 14 February and was taken to a shelter hospital on 15 February. This is for the treatment of patients with mild illness in Wuhan, the use of large-scale public facilities such as the stadium temporary creation.

During that time, the whole of Wuhan went to great lengths to increase the number of beds. On Feb. 1, when the Fire God Mountain Hospital entered the peak of labor rush, a project manager told Caijing that he had slept only three hours in those three days. His wife had a high fever in his hometown, and his 6-year-old child was at home to take care of her, "It was a really hard time. "

On Feb. 4, the first 45 patients were admitted to Vulcan Mountain Hospital, which will provide 1,000 beds. On February 8, the Wuhan Thunder Mountain Hospital was put into operation, gradually opening 1,500 beds. Wuhan First Batch 3"the cabin hospital" opens in succession, uses in admitting the mild disease patient.

In addition, every effort has been made to increase material and personnel support. On February 5, Wuhan's maximum nucleic acid detection capacity has reached 6000-8000 daily. As of February 12, the National Health Commission sent a total of 189 medical teams, 21,569 medical staff to Hubei, all sides just slightly relieved. A doctor at the Wuhan Union Hospital worked for a month and finally got a few days off in early February, when the Central Hospital in Wuhan began arranging shifts.

On Feb. 10, the secretary and director of the Hubei Provincial Health Commission were both removed from their posts. Later, the main leaders of Hubei Province and Wuhan Province were replaced. On February 13th Ying Yong became party secretary of Hubei Province and Wang Zhonglin of Wuhan.

From the beginning of February, Volunteers Wang Chen confidence, call to help the number of patients significantly reduced.

The workload of the Wuhan Red Cross, which is responsible for material donations, has also stabilized. On January 24, the Red Cross in Wuhan opened 17 calls, almost all of them to donate money and materials, and the receiving team received a lot of criticism because of the red cross-related negative news, a Red Cross worker told Caijing that volunteers were often scolded and cried during those days.

Since then, fewer people have called to donate, and more have asked about supplies and money transfers. By the end of February, the number of calls from the Wuhan Red Cross answering team had dwindled to 11, with a peak of more than 100 volunteers.

A volunteer who had worked in the reception team told Caijing that the donations were getting smaller, and he felt he couldn't make much of a difference, so he left the Red Cross to help the medical team.

Wuhan in all aspects of the situation is improving, but the spread of the epidemic pressure is still great.

The fever clinic is finally free

February 14, Wuhan, the breath of spring is more and more rich, roadside trees in clusters of Small Pink Plum Open, attracted sparse passers-by stop, take photos. On the same day, the central committee went to Hubei to guide the group to release the news: to play a good Battle of Wuhan, Hubei Defense War Comprehensive General Offensive.

As the battleground shifted from hospitals to communities, designated hospitals were very different. At around 11 a.m. on Feb. 22, at the door of the nucleic acid collection room at Wuhan No. 7 Hospital, Liu Yang had a rare chance to sit around for a while, the megaphone at hand becoming redundant.

On This Day, the fever clinic at seven hospitals was unusually empty. There's no one waiting outside the second floor clinic. Nearly a week, about 50 people a day, most of them suspected patients from quarantined hotels, come in for follow up checks, or people who are about to return to work for medical checks, said a staff member who conducted the consultation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
February 22 at about 11:00 am, the fever clinic of Wuhan No. 7 Hospital was Empty Waiting Area. Photo by Xinna, CAIJING reporter

Wuhan now has 25,000 nucleic acid tests a day. On February 21, the stock of nucleic acid tests for the "four categories of people" with clinical diagnosis, suspected cases of fever, close contacts in the central isolation point in Wuhan was completely cleared; starting on February 22, wuhan plans to close the books on anyone who needs a nucleic acid test.

The hospitals that treated the confirmed patients stabilized, but the workload of the community staff did not decrease at all, only shifted the focus. The primary channel for all fever patients is the community, which keeps daily records of residents'health, contacts hospitals, and includes transportation.

On Feb. 15, wind, rain and snow hit Wuhan, and Liu Jing received a phone call that day to pack her bags and rush to a shelter hospital. "Most of the procedures are very tight, " she said. She had been called by city officials about an hour after receiving the positive results on Feb. 14.

That night Liu Jing took the initiative to call the community contact how to enter the shelter hospital isolation, but did not contact. On the morning of February 15, the next community staff called, offered to Liu Jing home for comprehensive disinfection, but confirmed the address found not in the jurisdiction. At noon that day, Liu Jing's community called to tell her to go to the shelter hospital to pick up the matter.

At two o'clock in the afternoon, the driver picked up a bus of eight people one by one, drove to castle peak shelter hospital, the other side said she was not on the list. It was verified that she should be sent to the Dunkou Shelter Hospital. "We couldn't blame the driver for not being followed, " Ms. Liu said. "We told the driver to take it easy and drive slowly during the blizzard. "

In a community in Hongshan district of Wuhan City, workers have been working around the clock for a month. A community leader told Caijing that she received more than 100 calls for help every day. Early community workers had limited protective equipment, "We have done our best, " he said, not daring to touch the fever patients directly. After the supplies are enough, he has to deal with all kinds of cumbersome work procedures, including filling out forms, taking photos, docking with government departments at all levels, and so on, i have to take on six leaders by myself.

They have bigger fish to FRY. In order to truly complete the isolation task, the comprehensive screening is proposed once again. February 17-19, Wuhan, three days to carry out a centralized network of large-scale clearance, community-based, thorough screening of all types of patients and close contacts.

To this end, February 16 in Hubei Province, urban and rural all village groups, communities, communities, residential areas, the implementation of the most strict 24-hour closed-type management.

"This was the most rigorous screening, at least I did get a call and a house call, " said the Wuhan University professor, who recalled that the screening had not been thorough enough.

February 9, the community daily household statistics is to deal with the Errand, to link registration, reported safe, left contact information after it does not matter, I took the initiative to register the first day, i didn't register for the next two days and nobody called me,"a Wuhan resident told CAIJING.".

A Wuhan resident who lives near the Wuhan Union Hospital told Caijing that they need to take their own temperature every day and report it in the community, but no one urged them to do so. Because some communities need to fill in body temperature twice a day, community owners when volunteers, docking grid, to help statistics and urge.

About 60 percent of the 1,500 people sampled in an online survey recently released by the Central China Normal University did not know if there was a confirmed patient in the neighborhood, suspected patients were not quarantined, and 70 percent did not know if close contacts were not quarantined.

The community needs to announce specific information to the residents, such as the outbreak alert. "Our community did not post any epidemic alert, nor did the community inform the owner. Finally, the owner strongly requested a notice on February 14, only to learn that there were 11 confirmed cases and 8 suspected cases in the community. " The resident's unit had two confirmed cases and one suspected case, so he and his family avoid going out, the next floor once a week, unless ordering meat, vegetables and other necessities of life.

It's not good, but it's GonNa get better

Living material shortage, some practical difficulties also appear in Wuhan.

Volunteers Chen Xingxu found that the "city" after the financial constraints of the elderly is the most difficult. He learned that an old man in order to save a few yuan of food money, secretly run over the wall out of the community, want to buy their own food outside.

A criminal investigator from the Public Security Department said on Feb. 20 that it was difficult to guard the entrance of residential areas at the lower levels, "there was an 86-year-old mother-in-law who used to go out every day for all sorts of reasons and ended up coming back with just a box of instant noodles. After a few days of total closure, the community workers and volunteers struggled. Today, it was the neighbors who helped her confirm that she had sold out of the 10-yuan-a-catty she drank every day, and finally gave up."

In Times of scarcity, supplies are being donated without compensation and attempts are being made to Disturb the water and catch a fish.

On February 18, a message was sent from a wechat group of owners in Hengdacheng community, east-west Lake District, Wuhan, that live fish, 10 Jin and 100 yuan, including grass carp, Crucian carp and silver carp, could be delivered to their homes.

After one owner paid, she received the fish at a sealed exit around 10 p.m. . It was dark. She didn't see what was in the bag. When she got home, she found only silver carp and bream, mostly dead fish.

"If the price has doubled by his standard, we can understand the price increase, but we can not understand the cheating, " the owner told Caijing.

"Not all communities can be well controlled. Some communities have group purchases at 10:00 am every day, and people take their goods 1 meter apart, but some communities have a little bit of confusion in management, group purchases continue, and people are hurt when picking up goods, which may affect the effect of segregation, " said the Wuhan University professor.

Medical personnel from all over the country are coming to support Wuhan. A 78-room hotel in Wuhan was requisitioned on February 20 to house a team of medical staff to support the city. The hotel manager told Caijing that it was not a good time to make arrangements without discussing the cost.

The man approached was a middle-aged man with a "volunteer" sign on his chest. He worked at the school and was asked to do liaison work. He will be responsible for all aspects of the lives of the medical staff assisting the Han people. For example, the hotel can not provide food, he's GonNa help us with all the reservations.

On February 22, Wuhan City Prevention and Control Headquarters announced the previous day's epidemic-related data, "four categories of personnel" , confirmed patients column, zero home.

Completing the quarantine is the first step in Wuhan's efforts to control the epidemic and restore health, though there is still a long way to go.

Wang Chen is now more worried about his own livelihood. Because the factory can not start, he does not have a stable source of income, the wages of his employees can not be cut off, and the interest on bank loans are increasing every day. He does not know how long he can survive, but I still want to get through it.

Liu Jing, Liu Yang, Li fan and Li Xiaoyi are aliases
